{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"924c39ab-edc9-45e5-847e-627a4cc4f4e6","content":"## The Issue\n\n**.NET MAUI Android requires the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17**, which is bundled with the MAUI workload. While Adoptium Temurin is a valid JDK 17, the .NET Android SDK may not recognize it correctly or can have subtle compatibility issues with non-Microsoft distributions.\n\n## Fix\n\n**Option 1 — Use the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK (recommended):**\n\n```bash\n# Reinstall the MAUI workload, which includes Microsoft OpenJDK 17\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\nThen **unset** your `JAVA_HOME` override so the build auto-discovers the bundled JDK:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Force the build to use your Temurin JDK:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n(Adjust the path to match your actual Temurin install location — verify with `/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17`.)\n\n---\n\n**Option 1 is strongly preferred** — it eliminates the mismatch entirely and is the officially supported configuration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c49132b5-0629-4655-8236-e8f929653778","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java.\n\nThe key issue here is likely related to .NET MAUI / .NET for Android's Java version requirements. Let me check what I know:\n\n- .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- However, there's been a known issue where .NET MAUI (particularly newer versions) requires the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution specifically, not just any JDK 17.\n\n\n- There's a documented compatibility issue where Adoptium/Temurin JDK distributions can cause build failures on certain platforms, and the .NET Android SDK may have trouble locating or properly using non-Microsoft JDK distributions.\n- The build system likely needs the JavaSdkDirectory environment variable properly configured to point to the correct JDK installation.\n- I'm thinking through what specific error they might be encountering—common ones involve version detection mismatches or UnsupportedClassVersion exceptions, though they've confirmed they have JDK 17 installed.\n\nThe real issue is likely that .NET 9 specifically requires the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK, but on macOS, Adoptium's Temurin JDK installs to a different directory structure than what the .NET Android workload expects, so the build system can't locate it properly even though JAVA_HOME might be set correctly. For .NET 8, JDK 17 is required with Microsoft's build being recommended, while .NET 9 maintains the same requirement. The real issue is that on macOS, Adoptium Temurin's path structure might not be recognized by the .NET Android build tools even though it's a valid JDK. The most reliable solution is installing the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17, which comes with the .NET MAUI workload and is what the Android SDK expects to find. Even with `JAVA_HOME` set, the build might not pick up the Temurin installation correctly. I think the clearest approach is to either use the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the MAUI workload, or explicitly configure `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file to point to the right JDK.","outputTokens":1794,"requestId":"9437:3FC561:13D8EB7:16462ED:6A0670DA"},"id":"b7a02c82-74a7-415b-acc1-e521d242bc09","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:03:58.810Z","parentId":"f3b24572-c2ca-44d3-a548-84ff57f0d918"}
